'''Russell Scott''' (born 1921), also known as '''Blinky the Clown''', was an [[United States|American]] [[clown]] who starred in a [[Denver]], [[Colorado]] television program called ''[[Blinky's Fun Club]]'' from 1958 until the show's cancellation in 1998.
''Blinky's Fun Club'' began in 1958 and originated from the studios of [[KKTV]] in Colorado Springs. In 1966 the show moved to [[KWGN]] in Denver and remained there until it was cancelled 1998.<ref name=malone>[http://www.malonetv.com Malone Media Group]</ref>
Mr. Scott holds several records: The Longest Career of a Children's Television Show Host - in the United States. The Second Longest Broadcast Career of a Children's Television Show Host - in the world. The Longest Career of a Television Clown in the world.
In 2004 he was inducted in the Silver Circle of the Heartland Chapter of the [[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]]. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emmyawards.tv/silver_circle/russell_scott.php |title=Heartland Chapter Silver Circle - Russell Scott |publisher=National Academy of Television Arts & Sciences |accessdate=December 10, 2010}}</ref> In 2005 Scott was inducted into the [http://www.broadcastprofessionals.net Broadcast Professionals of Colorado]'s Broadcast Pioneers Hall of Fame.<ref>[http://www.broadcastprofessionals.net/halloffame.html Broadcast Professionals of Colorado Hall of Fame]</ref> In 2006 he was the subject of a [[Documentary film|documentary]], titled ''Blinky'', produced and directed by Brian Malone.<ref name=malone/>
Scott owned Blinky's Antiques and Collectibles on South Broadway in [[Denver, Colorado]].<ref>[http://www.emmyawards.tv/silver_circle/russell_scott.php NATAS Heartland Silver Circle - Russell Scott]</ref> After 22 years, the shop closed in 2008.<ref name="9news">[http://www.9news.com/news/article.aspx?storyid=103747&catid=188 Blinky closes antique shop; goods to be auctioned]</ref>
